{
  "doc_id": "20734",
  "text": "One of the first logics capable of expressing resource requirements of agents was a version of Coalition Logic (CL) [CITATION_1] , called Resource-Bounded Coalition Logic (RBCL), where actions only consume (and don't produce) resources. It was introduced in [CITATION_2] with the primary motivation of modelling systems of resource-bounded reasoners, however the framework is sufficiently general to model any kind of action. The model-checking problem for this logic was shown to be decidable in [CITATION_3] in polynomial time in the transition system and the property and exponential in the number of resource types.",
